{"title_page": "Candi CdeBaca", "text_new": "{{short description|Denver politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name          = Candi CdeBaca\n|office        = Member of the [[Denver City Council]] from the 9th District \n|term_start    = July 15, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Albus Brooks]]\n|successor     = \n|image              =\n|imagesize          = \n|birth_date    = April 10, 1986\n|birth_place   = [[Elyria-Swansea, Denver]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n|otherparty    = [[Democratic Socialists of America]]\n|spouse        = \n|children      = \n|alma_mater    = [[University of Denver]]\n|website      = [https://www.denvergov.org/content/denvergov/en/denver-city-council/council-members/district-9.html City Council website]<br>\n[https://www.candicdebaca.com/ Campaign website]\n}}\n\nCandi CdeBaca is the Councilor for the 9th district of the [[Denver City Council]]. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and the [[Democratic Socialists of America]]. \n\n==Life and career==\nCdeBaca was born in Swansea, a neighborhood of Denver between rail lines and the [[Interstate 70]]. As a teenager, she came home one day to find her mother stuck in the street, unable to maneuver her wheelchair over a ramp-less curb. This experience led her to become an activist. In 2006, she co-founded Project VOYCE (Voices of Youth Changing Education), in response to the closure of her school, and helped to organize a [[class-action lawsuit]] against [[Denver Public Schools]]. CdeBaca was valedictorian and class president at [[Manual High School (Denver)|Manual High School]], and a first-generation high school graduate. Eventually, she earned bachelor's and master's degrees simultaneously from the [[University of Denver]], then left for [[Washington, D.C.]], to work in education advocacy. She returned to Denver in 2014, and once again became involved in local politics.<ref name=\"Post1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2019/07/15/candi-cdebaca-denver-democratic-socialist/|title=Incoming Denver Councilwoman Candi CdeBaca is a democratic socialist. Here\u2019s what that means.|last=Kenney|first=Andrew|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Denver City Council==\n\nCdeBaca was branded a [[communist]], for the [[anti-capitalist]] remarks she made during a candidate forum on April 7, 2019, advocating for \"[[community ownership]] of land, labor, resources, and distribution of those resources.\" In the days afterwards, the video was shared widely on [[right-wing]] news sites, and CdeBaca reportedly received hundreds of death and rape threats. [[Albus Brooks]], the incumbent councilor for the 9th district, was defeated by CdeBaca in a runoff election on June 4, 2019. Ahead of her swearing-in, CdeBaca clarified in an interview that she did not identify as a communist, would have preferred to run unaffiliated, and considered herself to be an [[anarchist]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/06/people-are-calling-denvers-newest-city-council-member-a-communist-but-shed-rather-be-called-an-anarchist/|title=People are calling Denver\u2019s newest city council member a communist \u2014 but she\u2019d rather be called an anarchist|date=June 25, 2019|first=Alex|last=Burness|publisher=[[The Colorado Independent]]|website=Raw Story|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe has faced pushback against a controversial tweet (February 28, 2020), in which she appeared to express support for the idea of spreading [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] at a [[Trump rally]]. A spokesperson claimed it was a \"sarcastic tweet, to call attention to the Trump administration\u2019s downplaying of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] as a \u2018hoax\u2019 no more dangerous than the common flu.\"<ref name=\"Post2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/03/candi-cdebaca-tweet-coronavirus-maga-rallies/|title=Denver Councilwoman Candi CdeBaca tweets \u201csarcastic\u201d endorsement of spreading coronavirus at GOP rallies|last=Swanson|first=Conrad|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Democratic Socialists of America who have held office in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CdeBaca, Candi}}\n[[Category:Women in Colorado politics]]\n[[Category:Colorado Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Denver City Council members]]\n[[Category:Members of the Democratic Socialists of America]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Denver politician}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name          = Candi CdeBaca\n|office        = Member of the [[Denver City Council]] from the 9th District \n|term_start    = July 15, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Albus Brooks]]\n|successor     = \n|image              =\n|imagesize          = \n|birth_date    = April 10, 1986\n|birth_place   = [[Elyria-Swansea, Denver]]\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]\n|otherparty    = [[Democratic Socialists of America]]\n|spouse        = \n|children      = \n|alma_mater    = [[University of Denver]]\n|website      = [https://www.denvergov.org/content/denvergov/en/denver-city-council/council-members/district-9.html City Council website]<br>\n[https://www.candicdebaca.com/ Campaign website]\n}}\n\nCandi CdeBaca is the Councilor for the 9th district of the [[Denver City Council]]. She is a member of the [[Democratic Party]] and the [[Democratic Socialists of America]]. \n\n==Life and career==\nCdeBaca was born in Swansea, a neighborhood of Denver between rail lines and the [[Interstate 70]]. As a teenager, she came home one day to find her mother stuck in the street, unable to maneuver her wheelchair over a ramp-less curb. This experience led her to become an activist. In 2006, she co-founded Project VOYCE (Voices of Youth Changing Education), in response to the closure of her school, and helped to organize a [[class-action lawsuit]] against [[Denver Public Schools]]. CdeBaca was valedictorian and class president at [[Manual High School (Denver)|Manual High School]], and a first-generation high school graduate. Eventually, she earned bachelor's and master's degrees simultaneously from the [[University of Denver]], then left for [[Washington, D.C.]], to work in education advocacy. She returned to Denver in 2014, and once again became involved in local politics.<ref name=\"Post1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2019/07/15/candi-cdebaca-denver-democratic-socialist/|title=Incoming Denver Councilwoman Candi CdeBaca is a democratic socialist. Here\u2019s what that means.|last=Kenney|first=Andrew|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|date=July 15, 2019|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Denver City Council==\n\nCdeBaca was branded a [[communist]], for the [[anti-capitalist]] remarks she made during a candidate forum on April 7, 2019, advocating for \"[[community ownership]] of land, labor, resources, and distribution of those resources.\" In the days afterwards, the video was shared widely on [[right-wing]] news sites, and CdeBaca reportedly received hundreds of death and rape threats. [[Albus Brooks]], the incumbent councilor for the 9th district, was defeated by CdeBaca in a runoff election on June 4, 2019. Ahead of her swearing-in, CdeBaca clarified in an interview that she did not identify as a communist, would have preferred to run unaffiliated, and considered herself to be an [[anarchist]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/06/people-are-calling-denvers-newest-city-council-member-a-communist-but-shed-rather-be-called-an-anarchist/|title=People are calling Denver\u2019s newest city council member a communist \u2014 but she\u2019d rather be called an anarchist|date=June 25, 2019|first=Alex|last=Burness|publisher=[[The Colorado Independent]]|website=Raw Story|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nShe has faced pushback against a controversial tweet (February 28, 2020), in which she appeared to express support for the idea of spreading [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] at a [[Trump rally]]. A spokesperson claimed it was a \"sarcastic tweet, to call attention to the Trump administration\u2019s downplaying of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] as a \u2018hoax\u2019 no more dangerous than the common flu.\"<ref name=\"Post2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/03/candi-cdebaca-tweet-coronavirus-maga-rallies/|title=Denver Councilwoman Candi CdeBaca tweets \u201csarcastic\u201d endorsement of spreading coronavirus at GOP rallies|last=Swanson|first=Conrad|publisher=[[The Denver Post]]|date=March 3, 2020|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Democratic Socialists of America who have held office in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CdeBaca, Candi}}\n[[Category:Women in Colorado politics]]\n[[Category:Colorado Democrats]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Women city councillors in the United States]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women politicians]]\n[[Category:Denver City Council members]]\n[[Category:Members of the Democratic Socialists of America]]\n[[Category:American anarchists]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Candi_CdeBaca"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Frake", "text_new": "{{short description|British chef}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Thomas Frake\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Dartford]], [[Kent]]\n| years_active = 2020\u2013present\n| occupation   = Chef\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Frake''' is a British cook and winner of the [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef 2020]] UK TV show competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52329700?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment_and_arts&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=MasterChef: BBC One cookery show chooses 2020 champion, 17 April 2020|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-17/masterchef-2020-winner-thomas-frake/|title=MasterChef crown their 2020 winner after nail-biting finale, 17 April 2020|website=Radio Times}}</ref>\n\nHis final menu was to prepare a three-course meal for judges [[John Torode]] and [[Gregg Wallace]]. Frake's winning menu consisted of:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/masterchef-winner|title=MasterChef 2020 champion announced, 17 April 2020|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n* ''First course: Monk fish Scampi - Monk fish tails in a beer batter, flavoured with smoked Paprika and Cayenne pepper, pickled Fennel, gherkins and onions and Tartare sauce topped with Tarragon''\n* ''Main course: Ox cheek braised in black treacle, bone marrow and Porto beer with crispy onions, shredded Brussels sprouts with bacon, carrots cooked in carrot juice and topped with onion seeds and Horseradish mash all served in the Ox cheek braising juices ''\n* ''Dessert: Salted caramel custard tart, topped with grated Nutmeg, caramel and orange zest popcorn and a popcorn ice cream.'''\n\n==Early life==\n\nFrake (born 1988) was raised in [[Dartford]], [[Kent]]. He began cooking at the age of seven and was influenced by his mother and both of his grandmothers. He attended [[Dartford Grammar School]] before taking a [[Financial Technology]] degree at the [[University of Sussex]] graduating in 2008. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/kent-banker-wins-masterchef-final-225850/|title=Dartford banker Thomas Frake wins MasterChef final, 17 April 2020|website=KentOnline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n  | before = [[Irini Tzortzoglou]]\n  | title  = [[BBC]] [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]] champion\n  | years  = 2020\n  | after  = TBA\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{twitter|/thomasfrake}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frake, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British chef}}\n{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Thomas Frake\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   =\n| birth_place  = [[Dartford]], [[Kent]]\n| years_active = 2020\u2013present\n| occupation   = Chef\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Thomas Frake''' is a British cook and winner of the [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|MasterChef 2020]] UK TV show competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52329700?intlink_from_url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment_and_arts&link_location=live-reporting-story|title=MasterChef: BBC One cookery show chooses 2020 champion, 17 April 2020|website=BBC}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/tv/2020-04-17/masterchef-2020-winner-thomas-frake/|title=MasterChef crown their 2020 winner after nail-biting finale, 17 April 2020|website=Radio Times}}</ref>\n\nHis final menu was to prepare a three-course meal for judges [[John Torode]] and [[Gregg Wallace]]. Coombes winning menu consisted of:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2020/masterchef-winner|title=MasterChef 2020 champion announced, 17 April 2020|website=BBC}}</ref>\n\n* ''First course: Monk fish Scampi - Monk fish tails in a beer batter, flavoured with smoked Paprika and Cayenne pepper, pickled Fennel, gherkins and onions and Tartare sauce topped with Tarragon''\n* ''Main course: Ox cheek braised in black treacle, bone marrow and Porto beer with crispy onions, shredded Brussels sprouts with bacon, carrots cooked in carrot juice and topped with onion seeds and Horseradish mash all served in the Ox cheek braising juices ''\n* ''Dessert: Salted caramel custard tart, topped with grated Nutmeg, caramel and orange zest popcorn and a popcorn ice cream.'''\n\n==Early life==\n\nFrake (born 1988) was raised in [[Dartford]], [[Kent]]. He began cooking at the age of seven and was influenced by his mother and both of his grandmothers. He attended [[Dartford Grammar School]] before taking a [[Financial Technology]] degree at the [[University of Sussex]] graduating in 2008. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kentonline.co.uk/dartford/news/kent-banker-wins-masterchef-final-225850/|title=Dartford banker Thomas Frake wins MasterChef final, 17 April 2020|website=KentOnline}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{start box}}\n{{succession box\n  | before = [[Irini Tzortzoglou]]\n  | title  = [[BBC]] [[MasterChef (UK TV series)|Masterchef]] champion\n  | years  = 2020\n  | after  = TBA\n}}\n{{end box}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{twitter|/thomasfrake}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Frake, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Reality cooking competition winners]]\n", "name_user": "Anthonycarrol", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Frake"}
{"title_page": "Ernie Sabella", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ernie Sabella\n| image         =\n| imagesize     = 250px\n| caption       =\n| birthname     = Ernest Sabella\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1949|09|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States|U.S.]]<ref name=\"Film Reference\"/>\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| othername     =\n| occupation    = Actor\n| yearsactive   = 1976\u2013present\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Cheryl Sabella|1999}}\n| known_for   = \n| notable_works = \n| website       =\n}}\n\n'''Ernest Sabella'''<ref name=\"Film Reference\">{{cite web|title=Ernie Sabella Biography|url=http://www.filmreference.com/film/80/Ernie-Sabella.html|website=FilmReference.com|publisher=Film Reference|accessdate=August 23, 2015|archivedate=April 18, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150418231029/http://www.filmreference.com/film/80/Ernie-Sabella.html}}</ref> (born September 19, 1949) is an American actor.  He is the voice of [[Timon and Pumbaa|Pumbaa]] from ''[[The Lion King (franchise)|The Lion King]]'' franchise, and played the role of Leon Carosi in the TV sitcom ''[[Saved By The Bell]]''. His work in [[Broadway theatre]] includes starring roles in ''[[Guys and Dolls (musical)|Guys and Dolls]]'' and ''[[Man of La Mancha]]''.\n\n==Life and career==\nBorn in [[Westchester County, New York]], Sabella graduated from the [[University of Miami]],<ref name=\"lasvegassun.com\"/> where he studied at the Department of Theatre Arts and performed at the university's [[Jerry Herman Ring Theatre]].\n\nHis stage credits include ''[[The Robber Bridegroom (musical)|The Robber Bridegroom]]'' (1976), ''Little Johnny Jones'' (1982), ''[[Guys and Dolls (musical)|Guys and Dolls]]'' (1992) as Harry the Horse, ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' (1996), ''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]'' as Amos Hart (replacement), ''[[Man of La Mancha]]'' (2002, as [[Sancho Panza]]) and ''[[Sweet Charity]]'' (2005).<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-cast-staff/ernie-sabella-73258 Sabella Broadway\"] ibdb.com, retrieved February 15, 2018</ref>\n\nFilm credits include ''[[Quiz Show (film)|Quiz Show]]'' (1994) as the car salesman, ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'' (1997) as Aldo Hooper, [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]'s ''[[The Lion King]]'' (1994) and multiple [[sequel]]s and spin-offs as [[Timon and Pumbaa#Pumbaa|Pumbaa]]. He also has worked with [[Nathan Lane]], who had voiced [[Timon and Pumbaa#Timon|Timon]], in ''[[Guys and Dolls (musical)|Guys and Dolls]]'', ''[[Mouse Hunt]]'', ''[[The Producers (2005 film)|The Producers]]'' (in a deleted scene) and ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]''. In the latter production, Sabella portrayed Marcus Lycus while Lane played Pseudolus. Sabella also joined Lane for his ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' monologue, where they sang \"[[Hakuna Matata (song)|Hakuna Matata]]\".\n\nOn television, Sabella portrayed apartment manager Lou Donatelli in the [[Jason Bateman]] comedy ''[[It's Your Move]]'' (1984\u201385).<ref name=guide/> He appeared in an episode of ''Cheers'' titled \"Love Thy Neighbor\" (Season Four Episode Eight air date November 21, 1985)<ref name=guide/> in which he played the role of a private investigator named Santo Carbone, who was Carla Tortelli's cousin. He played store owner and landlord Donald Twinkacetti on ''[[Perfect Strangers (TV series)|Perfect Strangers]]'' (1986\u20131987). \n<ref name=guide/> He played Leo in the short-lived [[situation comedy]] ''[[Encore! Encore!]]'' starring [[Nathan Lane]] (2000).<ref name=guide/> Sabella had a five-episode stint on ''[[Saved by the Bell]]'' in 1991 as Leon Carosi,<ref name=guide/> an uptight resort manager and owner who employed the main cast's characters. [[Leah Remini]] was featured as his daughter. His other [[recurring role]]s include the lazy teacher Mr. Petrachelli on ''[[That's So Raven]]'' (2003), the floundering attorney Harland Bassett on ''[[The Practice]]'' (2000-2001), and characters on ''[[Newhart]]'' (1983).<ref name=guide/>\n\nIn the ''[[Quantum Leap]]'' episode \"Catch a Falling Star\", he played the dual role of Manny, a stage actor, and [[Sancho Panza]], Manny's character in a touring production of ''Man of La Mancha''. Sabella had a brief appearance as a naked man on a [[Subway (rail)|subway]] train in a 1992 episode of ''[[Seinfeld]]'' titled \"[[The Subway (Seinfeld)|The Subway]]\".<ref name=guide/> \n\nHe starred in a series of [[television commercial]]s for [[NyQuil]] cold medicine in 1994 and was seen in a [[MasterCard]] commercial (2007).\n\nSabella co-starred as Sidney Bernstein in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical comedy]] ''[[Curtains (musical)|Curtains]]'', which opened officially on March 22, 2007<ref>{{cite news  | last = Bacalzo  | first = Dan  | title = Full Cast Set for Broadway's Curtains: Ernie Sabella Joins Musical  | work = TM Theater News  | publisher = TheaterMania Inc.  | date = January 4, 2007  | url = http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/9799  | accessdate = January 12, 2007  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070306105408/http://www.theatermania.com/content/news.cfm/story/9799  | archive-date = March 6, 2007  | url-status = dead  }}</ref> and ran until June 29, 2008.\n\nHe played the role of apartment building superintendent Leon in the 9th episode \"Hold Outs\" of the 6th season (2015) of the [[CBS]] police procedural drama ''[[Blue Bloods (TV series)|Blue Bloods]]''.\n<ref name=guide>[http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/ernie-sabella/credits/149629/ \"Ernie Sabella Credits\"] \ntvguide.com, retrieved February 15, 2018</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Sabella reprised his voice role as Pumbaa in the TV pilot movie ''The Lion Guard: Return of the Roar''.\n\nIn 2016, Sabella became a full-time cast member for the [[Disney Junior]] television series ''[[The Lion Guard]]''.<ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/2015/11/17/lion-guard-james-earl-jones-mufasa ''Lion Guard''] ew.com</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSabella met his wife Cheryl backstage during a Broadway performance of ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' in 1996, they married in 1999.<ref>Gladstone, Douglas. [http://www.westchestermagazine.com/Westchester-Magazine/June-2014/Remember-The-Naked-Subway-Rider-In-Seinfeld-Meet-Ernie-Sabella/ \"Remember The Naked Subway Rider In Seinfeld? Meet Ernie Sabella\"] ''Westchester Magazine'', June 2014</ref><ref name=\"lasvegassun.com\">[https://lasvegassun.com/news/2002/jan/17/a-real-character-actor-ernie-sabella-sets-up-shop-/ \"A real character: Actor Ernie Sabella sets up shop in Southern Nevada\"] ''Las Vegas Sun'', January 17, 2002</ref> His wife works as a computer programmer in their home town.<ref name=\"lasvegassun.com\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 1984 || ''[[City Heat]]'' || Ballistics Expert || \n|-\n| 1986 || ''[[Tough Guys (1986 film)|Tough Guys]]'' || Hotel Clerk ||\n|-\n| 1988 || ''[[Fright Night Part 2]]'' || Dr. Harrison || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1990 || ''[[Faith (1990 film)|Faith]]'' || Stanley || \n|-\n| ''[[Going Under (1991 film)|Going Under]]'' || The Mole || \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1994 || ''[[The Lion King]]'' || [[Timon and Pumbaa|Pumbaa]] (voice) ||\n|-\n| ''[[Quiz Show (film)|Quiz Show]]'' || Car Salesman || \n|-\n| 1995 || ''[[Roommates]]'' || Stash || \n|-\n| 1996 || ''Around the World with Timon & Pumbaa'' || Pumbaa (voice) || Direct-to-video\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 1997 || ''[[In & Out (film)|In & Out]]'' || Aldo Hopper || \n|-\n| ''[[Mouse Hunt]]'' || Maury, the Cat Care Society Owner || \n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[The Lion King 2: Simba's Pride]]'' || Pumbaa (voice) || Direct-to-video\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[The Out-of-Towners (1999 film)|The O