'' (known as '''CRRC''') is a Chinese publicly traded [[rolling stock]] manufacturer and is the largest rolling stock manufacturer in the world eclipsing [[Alstom]] and [[Siemens Mobility|Siemens]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-01-20/france-raises-pressure-on-vestager-to-allow-siemens-alstom-deal|title=Siemens-Alstom Deal Teeters on Brink Amid Fierce Lobbying|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/blogs/kevin-smith/will-alstom-siemens-merger-check-crrcs-international-expansion.html|title=Will Alstom-Siemens merger check CRRC's international expansion?|last=Smith|first=Kevin|access-date=2017-09-29|language=en-gb}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-02-04/european-champions-may-yet-rise-from-the-siemens-alstom-rubble|title=Siemens-Alstom's Expected EU Veto Unleashes Political Storm|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref> \n\nAs of 2016 it had 183,061 employees<ref name=\"CRRC2016AR\" />, and was formed on 1 June 2015 with the merger of [[China CNR|CNR]] and [[CSR Corporation Limited|CSR]]. The parent company of CRRC Corp., Ltd. is [[CRRC Group]], a [[state-owned enterprise]] that was supervised by the [[State-owned Assets Supervision and Administration Commission of the State Council]]. The State Council also owned additional shares via [[China Securities Finance]] and [[Central Huijin Investment]].\n\n==History==\n[[CNR Group]] and [[CSR Group]], once one company {{ill|China National Railway Locomotive & Rolling Stock Industry Corporation|zh|\u4e2d\u56fd\u94c1\u8def\u673a\u8f66\u8f66\u8f86\u5de5\u4e1a\u603b\u516c\u53f8}} (LORIC), were separated in 2002.<ref name=nyt20141230/><ref>[[wikisource:zh:\u56fd\u52a1\u9662\u5173\u4e8e\u7ec4\u5efa\u4e2d\u56fd\u5317\u65b9\u673a\u8f66\u8f66\u8f86\u5de5\u4e1a\u96c6\u56e2\u516c\u53f8\u6709\u5173\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u6279\u590d]] (in Chinese)</ref>\n\nIn late 2014 CNR Group and CSR Group agreed to merge, subject to approval by the Chinese state - under the agreement CNR Group would formally acquire CSR Group (but [[CSR Corporation Limited]] would acquired [[China CNR|China CNR Corporation Limited]]), and the combined business then be renamed to [[CRRC Group]] and '''CRRC Corporation Limited''' respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.chinacnr.com/Portals/0/LTN20150518007.pdf|title=CSR and CNR Joint Announcement|access-date=11 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509094428/http://en.chinacnr.com/Portals/0/LTN20150518007.pdf|archive-date=9 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.chinacnr.com/Portals/0/LTN201504271770.pdf|title=CSR and CNR Joint Announcement Update|access-date=17 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509235328/http://en.chinacnr.com/Portals/0/LTN201504271770.pdf|archive-date=9 May 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Rationales given for the merger were increased efficiency, and the ability to better compete internationally with combined resources.<ref name=rgi20141231/>\n\nThe merger came into effect 1 June 2015, with each CNR share exchanged for 1.1 CSR shares - the combined company became the largest railway rolling stock manufacturer in the world, and had over 90% of the China market. Total employment of the combine was 175,700 persons, and the share capital was valued at {{CNY|link=yes|27.289 [[1,000,000,000|billion]]}}.<ref name=rgi20150602/>\n\nAfter formation, CRRC began efforts to expand overseas; after being awarded a 284 vehicle order (since expanded to 404 vehicles) for metro cars for [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]'s [[Red Line (MBTA)|Red]] and [[Orange Line (MBTA)|Orange]] lines with a US$556.6 million bid in October 2014, the company started to construct a {{convert|13900|m2}} assembly plant in [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] at a former Westinghouse plant<ref name=\"irjoct2014\"/> beginning in September 2015.<ref name=\"rgplant2014\"/> Manufacturing work began in April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/business-news/index.ssf/2018/04/first_t_car_shells_arrive_at_crrc_execs.html|title=First Orange Line T car shells arrive at CRRC factory in Springfield|date=Apr 11, 2018|work=masslive|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2015 production began at a rolling stock plant in [[Batu Gajah]], [[Perak]], [[Malaysia]], a satellite of [[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]], and the corporation's first plant outside China.<ref name=\"irjjul2015\"/> Additionally the former CSR had acquired [[Emprendimientos Ferroviarios]] in Argentina in 2014 and announced in 2016 that they would begin maintenance and production of new rolling stock for export in the country.<ref name=\"arg1\"/><ref name=\"arg2\">{{cite news|title=Una empresa china quiere instalarse en la Argentina para fabricar vagones|url=http://www.lanacion.com.ar/1941835-una-empresa-china-quiere-instalarse-en-la-argentina-para-fabricar-vagones|accessdate=28 September 2016|work=La Nacion|date=27 September 2016}}</ref> Argentina had previously purchased a variety of rolling stock from the company over the years, including 704 [[CSR EMU (Argentina)|EMU cars]], 81 DMU cars, 44 passenger locomotives, 360 carriages, 107 freight locomotives and 3,500 freight cars, in addition to the 150 [[Buenos Aires Underground 200 Series|200 Series]] cars for the [[Buenos Aires Underground|Subte]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Dietrich acord\u00f3 con gigante ferroviario chino instalar taller en el pa\u00eds|url=http://www.cronista.com/economiapolitica/Dietrich-acordo-con-gigante-ferroviario-chino-instalar-taller-en-el-pais-20160928-0078.html|accessdate=28 September 2016|work=El Cronista|date=28 September 2016|language=es-LA}}</ref><ref name=\"arg2\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=CRRC reitera sus intenciones de instalarse en la Argentina|url=http://enelsubte.com/noticias/crrc-reitera-sus-intenciones-de-instalarse-en-la-argentina/|accessdate=30 September 2016|work=EnElSubte|date=30 September 2016|language=es-ES}}</ref> In 2017, the Argentine government purchased an additional 200 EMUs from CRRC.<ref>{{cite news|title=Compran 200 coches el\u00e9ctricos adicionales para la l\u00ednea Roca|url=http://enelsubte.com/noticias/compran-200-coches-electricos-adicionales-para-la-linea-roca/|accessdate=15 January 2018|work=enelSubte.com|date=4 January 2018|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-2015, CRRC formed a freight wagon joint venture, [[Vertex Railcar]], as a minority partner with Hong Kong-based private equity firm [[Majestic Legend Holdings]] to establish production in [[Wilmington, North Carolina]] at a former [[Terex]] facility.<ref name=\"wilminton2015\"/> CRRC provided railcar designs and some components, and Majestic Legend  invested US$6 million;<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wilmingtonbiz.com/more_news/2015/06/19/vertex%C3%83%C2%A2%C3%A2%E2%80%9A%C2%AC%C3%8B%E2%80%A0signs_of_growth_or_trouble/13446 | title=Vertex: Signs Of Growth Or Trouble? | publisher=Wilmington Business Journal | date=19 June 2015 | accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref> the plant was operational by the beginning of 2016.<ref name=\"wilminton2016\"/> In August 2016, at the request of a letter from 55 US House of Representatives members alleging that Vertex was being unfairly subsidized by the Chinese government, the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] began an investigation into whether the Chinese investment in Vertex constituted a national security risk.<ref name=\"sno\"/> 42 US Senators sent a similar letter in September, conveying concerns about the state-owned enterprises behind Vertex.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.moran.senate.gov/public/_cache/files/6/d/6d4f64f1-6129-4c75-99b8-6eff6874b42d/92FCFF776C1C8DE429273D4B2C830622.09.28.2016-to-treasury-secretary-lew-re-cfius-investigation-on-vertex.pdf | title=Letter to Treasury Secretary Lew regarding CFIUS investigation on Vertex | publisher=Sen. Jerry Moran | date=29 September 2017 | accessdate=8 May 2017}}</ref> The Treasury Department released its report in December and found that the joint ownership was not a risk.<ref name=\"sno\">{{cite web | url=http://www.starnewsonline.com/news/20161214/vertexs-deal-with-china-cleared-by-feds | title=Vertex's deal with China cleared by Feds | publisher=Star-News Online | date=14 December 2016 | accessdate=5 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015, Yu Weiping, one of the vice-president of the company, stated the company planned to double overseas sales over five years, with North American passenger rail being one target.<ref name=\"bloom2015\"/> Interim six month financial results for the new company showed an increase in overseas revenue of over 60%. Half year revenue was {{CNY|91.8 billion}}, with a gross profit of {{CNY|19.5 billion}}. Non rail revenue (car equipment, generators) was {{CNY|20.94 billion}}.<ref name=\"irjprofit2015\"/>\n\nIn March 2016, [[CRRC Qingdao Sifang]] was awarded a contract to build 400 [[7000 series (CTA)|7000-series]] cars for the [[Chicago Transit Authority]] (CTA), with an option for another 446 cars. The cost of the contract was US$632 million up to US$1.3 billion with options; as a consequence CRRC began development of a US$40 million assembly factory in Chicago, designed by Itasca, IL-based Cornerstone Architects Ltd.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/north-america/crrc-to-build-up-to-846-metro-cars-for-chicago.html| title=CRRC to build up to 846 metro cars for Chicago| first=Keith| last=Barrow| date=9 March 2016| website=www.railjournal.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/crrc-usa-idUSL5N16I0LS| title=China's CRRC wins $1.3 bln deal to supply Chicago rail cars| website=Reuters| date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2017, Quincy, Massachusetts based CRRC MA was awarded a contract by [[SEPTA]] to construct 45 bi-level rail cars with the option for 10 additional cars for delivery in October 2019. The SEPTA order will be built at the Springfield plant<ref>http://www.crrcgc.cc/ma</ref> and car shell manufactured from the Tangshan plant.<ref>https://www.railjournal.com/rolling-stock/crrc-puts-septa-double-deck-coach-design-to-the-test/</ref> CRRC was selected over Hyundai Rotem and Bombardier, which also bid on the bi-level contract and had each produced equipment for SEPTA in the past.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://planphilly.com/articles/2017/03/17/septa-to-pick-massachusetts-based-company-to-build-bilevel-railcars-over-hyundai-rotem-in-south-philly| title=SEPTA to pick Massachusetts-based company to build bilevel railcars over Hyundai Rotem in South Philly| website=PlanPhilly| date=17 March 2017| first=Jim| last=Saska}}</ref> Later that month, CRRC was also awarded a contract to build 64 [[CRRC HR4000|HR4000]] cars for the [[Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Authority]] (LACMTA) that will replace [[Breda A650|existing vehicles]] on the agency's [[Red Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Red]] and [[Purple Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Purple]] lines, with an option for another 218 cars.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.progressiverailroading.com/mechanical/news/LA-Metro-inks-pact-with-CRRC-for-up-to-282-new-rail-cars--51154 | title=L.A. Metro inks pact with CRRC for up to 282 new rail cars | publisher=Progressive Railroading | date=24 March 2017 | accessdate=24 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe LACMTA order will result in a {{convert|41218|sqft|sqm}} assembly plant (installing propulsion, HVAC and other general assembly) being built in LA.<ref>http://www.crrcgc.cc/ma</ref>\n\n{{clear}}\n==Subsidiaries==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n\n===Locomotive ===\n* [[CRRC Beijing Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Datong Electric Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Qishuyan Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Luoyang Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Xiangfan Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive|CRRC Zhuzhou [Electric] Locomotive]]\n* [[CRRC Ziyang Locomotive]]\n\n===Rolling Stock===\n* [[CRRC February 7 Rolling Stock]]\n* [[CRRC Qiqihar Railway Rolling Stock]]\n** [[CRRC Harbin Rolling Stock]]\n** {{zh|s=\u5927\u8fde\u4e2d\u8f66\u5927\u9f50\u8f66\u8f86|l=Dalian CRRC Daqi Railway Rolling Stock}}\n* [[CRRC Meishan Rolling Stock]]\n* [[CRRC Nanjing Puzhen Rolling Stock]]\n* [[CRRC Shijiazhuang Rolling Stock]]\n* [[CRRC Taiyuan Railway Rolling Stock]]\n* [[CRRC Yangtze Rolling Stock]]\n** [[CRRC Xi'an Railway Rolling Stock]]\n{{col-3}}\n\n===Locomotive & Rolling Stock===\n* [[CRRC Chengdu]]\n* [[CRRC Dalian]]\n* [[CRRC Qingdao Sifang]]\n* [[CRRC Tangshan]]\n\n===Other===\n* [[CRRC Beijing Nankou Railway Transportation Machinery]]\n* [[CRRC Changchun Railway Vehicles]]\n* [[CRRC Dalian Locomotive Research Institute]]\n* [[CRRC Jinan Railway Vehicles Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Qingdao Sifang Rolling Stock Research Institute]]\n* [[CRRC Lanzhou Jinniu Railway Transportation Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Shijiazhuang Guoxiang Transportation Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Tangshan Railway Transportation Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Tianjin Railway Transport Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Yongji Xinshisu Electric Equipment]]\n* [[CRRC Zhuzhou Electric]]\n* CRRC Zhuzhou Institute (former Zhuzhou Electric Locomotive Research Institute) (100%)\n* [[Zhuzhou CRRC Times Electric]] (51.81%)\n{{col-3}}\n\n===Joint venture===\n* [[Bombardier Sifang Transportation]]\n\n===Overseas===\n* [[CRRC Massachusetts (United States)]]\n* [[CRRC Sifang America]]\n* [[Dynex Semiconductor]] (United Kingdom)<ref group=nb>Subsidiary of Zhuzhou CRRC Times Electric</ref>\n* [[Emprendimientos Ferroviarios]] (Argentina)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Other investments==\nOn 8 January 2016 CRRC Corporation purchased 13.06% stake of [[China United Insurance Holding]] ({{zh|s=\u4e2d\u534e\u4fdd\u9669}}) from [[China Insurance Regulatory Commission|China Insurance Security Fund]] for {{CNY|4.455&nbsp;billion}}.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.crrcgc.cc/Portals/73/Uploads/Files/2016/1-11/635881025282842048.pdf|title=Acquisition of 13.06% Equity Interests in China United Insurance|date=8 January 2016|access-date=13 October 2016|publisher=CRRC}}</ref> It also joint-owned [[Zhuzhou Times New Material Technology]] with parent company [[CRRC Group]]. In November 2016 the company (via [[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]]) confirmed plans to buy [[\u0160koda Transportation]] based in the [[Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/crrc-confirms-plan-to-buy-skoda-transportation.html|title=CRRC confirms plan to buy \u0160koda Transportation|date=30 November 2016|access-date=27 July 2017|publisher=[[Railway Gazette International]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.hkexnews.hk/listedco/listconews/SEHK/2016/1127/LTN20161127005.pdf|title=ANNOUNCEMENT IN RELATION TO PROPOSED OFFSHORE ACQUISITION BY A SUBSIDIARY|date=27 November 2016|access-date=27 September 2017|publisher=CRRC|via=Hong Kong Stock Exchange}}</ref>\n\n==Shareholders==\n{{as of|2016|12|31}}, CRRC was majority owned by [[CRRC Group]] directly and indirectly (via CRRC Financial and Securities Investment, {{zh|s=\u4e2d\u8f66\u91d1\u8bc1\u6295\u8d44}} for 1.64%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://stock.qq.com/a/20170803/048739.htm|title=\u5357\u8f66\u6295\u8d44\u5411\u4e2d\u8f66\u91d1\u8bc1\u65e0\u507f\u5212\u8f6c\u4e2d\u56fd\u4e2d\u8f66(01766)0.32%\u80a1\u672c|date=3 August 2017|access-date=28 September 2017|work=\u667a\u901a\u8d22\u7ecf\u7f51|language=Chinese|via=qq.com}}</ref>) for 55.91% of total share capital (all in [[A-share (mainland China)|A share]]).<ref name=CRRC2016AR/>{{rp|85}} Other entity of the central government, such as [[China Securities Finance]] (2.87%) and [[Central Huijin Investment]] (1.12%), also owned a minority stake.<ref name=CRRC2016AR/>{{rp|83}} In terms of different shares, [[BlackRock]] owned 6.13% [[H share]]s in [[Long (finance)|long position]] (267,971,072 number of shares), or 0.98% in terms of total share capital.<ref name=CRRC2016AR/>{{rp|85}} Himalaya Capital Investors, a [[Seattle]] based mutual fund also owned about 6.13% H shares in long position (267,904,000 number of shares).<ref>{{cite web |title=About our investing philosophy |url=http://www.himalayacapital.com/index.htm |website=himalayacapital.com |publisher=Himalaya Capital |accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=CRRC2016AR/>{{rp|85}} Other shareholders each owned less than 1% shares in terms of total share capital.<ref name=CRRC2016AR/>{{rp|83\u201385}}\n\n==Products==\n'''Steam Lokomotives'''\n* [[China Railways JS]]\n'''Diesel Lokomotives'''\n\n''For China Railways:''\n* [[China Railways DF]]\n* [[China Railways DF2]]\n* [[China Railways DF5]]\n* [[China Railways DF8]]\n* [[China Railways DF11]]\n* [[China Railways DF11G]]\n* [[China Railways NDJ3]]\n* [[China Railways HXN5]]\n* [[China Railways HXN5B]]\n''For export:''\n* [[CNR CKD8|CKD8]]\n'''Electric Locomotives'''\n\n''For China Railways:''\n* [[China Railways DJ|DJ]] \n* [[China Railways DJ1|DJ1]]\n* [[China Railways DJ2|DJ2]] \n* [[China Railways HXD1|HXD1]] licensed from [[Siemens]]\n* [[China Railways HXD1B|HXD1B]]\n* [[China Railways HXD1C|HXD1C]]\n* [[China Railways HXD1D|HXD1D]]\n* [[China Railways HXD1G|HXD1G]]\n* [[China Railways SS1|SS1]]\n* [[China Railways SS3|SS3]] inspired from Japanese locomotive\n* [[China Railways SS4|SS4]]\n* [[China Railways SS5|SS5]]\n* [[China Railways SS6|SS6]]  \n* [[China Railways SS6B|SS6B]]\n* [[China Railways SS8|SS8]]\n* [[China Railways SS9|SS9]]\n''For Export:'' \n* [[TM1]] ([[Iran]])\n* [[TM2]] (Iran)\n* [[TM3]] (Iran)\n* [[O'zbekiston]] ([[Uzbekistan]])\n* [[KZ4A]] ([[Kazakhstan]])\n* TFR [[South African Class 20E|Class 20E]] AC/ DC electric locomotives ([[South Africa]]){{citation needed|date=June 2017}}\n\n'''DMU and EMU:'''\n* [[CRRC Equator|Equator]]\n* [[CSR EMU (Argentina)]]\n* [[MZ 711]]\n* [[China Railways Class DJJ1|DJJ1]] ''\"Blue Arrow\"'' (archived)\n* [[DJJ2]] ''\"China Star\"''  (archived)\n* [[China Railways Class CJ6|CJ6]] ([[MRL East Coast Rail Link]])\n* [[Changsha\u2013Zhuzhou\u2013Xiangtan intercity railway]]\n*[[KTM Class 92]] ([[Malaysia]])\n*[[KTM Class 93]] ([[Malaysia]])\n* [[M\u017d 411]] for Macedonian Railways\n* [[Leo Express]]\n* [[Sri Lanka Railways]]\n**[[Sri Lanka Railways S9]]\n** [[Sri Lanka Railways S10]]\n** [[Sri Lanka Railways S12]]\n** [[Sri Lanka Railways S14 & S14A]]\n\n'''High-speed trains'''\n* [[CRH1]]\n**[[China Railways CRH1#CRH1A|CRH1A & CRH1B]]\n* [[China Railways CRH1#CRH1E| CRH1E]]\n**[[China Railways CRH1#CRH1A-A| CRH1A-A <br> CRH1E-250]]\n**[[Bombardier Zefiro#Zefiro 380|CRH380D & DL]]\n* [[CRH2]]\n**[[China Railways CRH2#CRH2A|CRH2A]]\n**[[China Railways CRH2#CRH2B|CRH2B]]\n**[[China Railways CRH2#CRH2C|CRH2C]]\n**[[China Railways CRH2#CRH2E|CRH2E]]\n**[[China Railways CRH2#CRH2E|CRH2E (New Batch, sleeper)]]\n* [[CRH3]]\n**[[CRH3#CRH380B/BL|CRH380B, BL & CL]]\n**[[China Railways CRH5|CRH5G]]\n* [[CRH5]]\n* [[CRH6]]\n* [[China Railways CRH380A|CRH380A]]\n**[[China Railways CRH380A|CRH380AL]]\n* [[Fuxing (train)|Fuxing Hao Class CR400AF]]\n**[[Fuxing (train)|CR300AF]]\n**[[Fuxing (train)|CR300BF]]\n**[[Fuxing (train)|CR400AF, -A & -B]]\n**[[Fuxing (train)|CR400BF, -A & -B]]\n\n'''Metro'''\n\n'''Tram/Light Rail'''\n\n==See also==\n* [[High-speed rail in China]]\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{reflist|group=nb}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs =\n\n<ref name=nyt20141230>{{cite news | newspaper=New York Times |date=30 December 2014 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2014/12/30/world/asia/ap-as-china-railway-merger.html?_r=0 |title=China's Top 2 Makers of Bullet Trains Merge| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150619134349/http://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2014/12/30/world/asia/ap-as-china-railway-merger.html?_r=0| archivedate = 19 June 2015 }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rgi20141231>{{cite news |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/cnr-and-csr-agree-merger-terms.html|title=CNR and CSR agree merger terms | website=Railway Gazette International|date=31 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=rgi20150602>{{cite news |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/chinese-rolling-stock-manufacturers-merge-to-form-crrc-corp.html |title=Chinese rolling stock manufacturers merge to form CRRC Corp | website=Railway Gazette International| date=2 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"rgplant2014\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/crrc-launches-construction-of-us-assembly-plant.html| title=Groundbreaking ceremony for CRRC's US assembly plant| date=4 September 2015| website=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wilminton2015\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/chinese-manufacturer-invests-in-us-wagon-venture.html| title=Chinese manufacturer invests in US wagon venture| date=6 July 2015| website=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"wilminton2016\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/us-chinese-joint-venture-delivers-first-wagons.html| title=US-Chinese joint venture delivers first wagons| date=22 January 2016| website=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"senior2015\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/people/single-view/view/senior-roles-filled-at-crrc.html| title=Senior roles filled at CRRC| date=25 June 2015| website=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"irjoct2014\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/north-america/cnr-selected-to-supply-new-trains-for-boston.html| title=CNR selected to supply new trains for Boston| first=Keith| last=Barrow| date=22 October 2014| website=International Railway Journal}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"irjjul2015\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/asia/crrc-opens-malaysian-rolling-stock-plant.html| title=CRRC opens Malaysian rolling stock plant| first=Keith| last=Barrow| date=13 July 2015| website=International Railway Journal}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"irjprofit2015\">{{cite web| url=http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/financial/crrc-first-half-profits-up-while-overseas-revenue-soars.html| title=CRRC first-half profits up while overseas revenue soars| first=David| last=Briginshaw| date=1 September 2015| website=International Railway Journal}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"arg1\">{{cite web| url=http://enelsubte.com/noticias/csr-adquiere-emfer-y-desembarca-la-argentina-3063/| title=CSR adquiere EMFER y desembarca en la Argentina| language=Spanish| date=26 February 2014 | website=En El Subte}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"bloom2015\">{{cite web| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-09-10/china-trainmaker-crrc-plans-to-double-overseas-sales-in-5-years| title=China Trainmaker CRRC Plans to Double Its Overseas Sales| website=Bloomberg L.P.| date=10 September 2015| first=Bonnie| last=Cao}}</ref>\n\n<!--\n\nWHAT FOR?\n\n<ref name=\"arg2\">{{cite web| url=http://mininterior.gov.ar/prensa/prensa.php?i=4489| title=Randazzo confirm\u00f3 en China que antes de fin de mes estar\u00e1n en Argentina todos los trenes 0km para el ramal Constituci\u00f3n - La Plata| language=Spanish| publisher=Ministerio del Interior, Obras P\u00fablicas y Vivienda| date=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n-->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|CRRC Corporation}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.crrcgc.cc/}}\n\n{{SSE 50 companies}}\n{{FTSE China A50 Index}}\n{{Hang Seng China Enterprises Index}}\n{{Hang Seng China 50 Index}}\n{{CRRC Group}}\n\n[[Category:Chinese brands]]\n[[Category:Chinese companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Companies in the CSI 100 Index]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in Beijing]]\n[[Category:Vehicle manufacturing companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Rolling stock manufacturers of China]]\n[[Category:Locomotive manufacturers of China]]\n[[Category:CRRC Group| 2]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of China]]\n[[Category:Companies formed by merger]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Combat Rubber Raiding Craft}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name   