{"title_page": "Kalan Haywood", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kalan Haywood\n| birth_name          = Kalan Haywood II\n| birth_date          = June 5, 1999 (age 20)\n| birth_place         = [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| office              = Member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]<br>from the 16th district\n| termstart           = January 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Leon Young]]\n| education           = [[Cardinal Stritch University]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Kalan Haywood II''' is an American politician, currently serving as a member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]], representing the 16th Assembly District.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHaywood was born on June 5, 1999 in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]. He graduated from the [[Rufus King International High School]] and is currently attending [[Cardinal Stritch University]] to earn a Bachelor of Arts degree in Business Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/2019/legislators/assembly/1929|title=Representative Kalan Haywood|website=docs.legis.wisconsin.gov|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Haywood's father, Kalan Haywood Sr., is the founder of a real estate development firm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://onmilwaukee.com/raisemke/articles/nns-kalan-haywood.html|title=\"What are we waiting for?\" Service is a family affair for Haywoods|date=2019-07-28|work=OnMilwaukee.com|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHaywood served as president of the City of Milwaukee Youth Council. He also worked as a non-profit consultant and was a member of the City of Milwaukee Restorative Justice Advisory Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Kalan_Haywood|title=Kalan Haywood|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nHaywood was 19-years-old when he won the Democratic [[primary election]] in August 2018 and the general election in November 2018, making him the youngest person serving in the Wisconsin Assembly and one of the youngest legislators in the country.<ref name=\"JSOnline\">[https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/09/28/teen-youngest-lawmaker-wisconsin-and-nation/1280007002/ At 19, Kalan Haywood will be the youngest lawmaker in Wisconsin \u2014 and likely the nation], by Molly Beck, in the ''[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]''; published September 28, 2018; retrieved November 14, 2018</ref><ref name=\"WUWM\">[http://www.wuwm.com/post/wisconsin-partisan-primary-2018-election-results Wisconsin Partisan Primary 2018 Election Results], by Lauren Sigfusson; at [[WUWM]]; published August 14, 2018; retrieved November 14, 2018; \"No Republicans are running\"</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Kate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/13/us/young-candidates-elections.html|title=In New Class of Young Lawmakers, a Former Girl Scout Goes to the Statehouse|date=2018-11-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wisconsin State Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haywood, Kalan}}\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Kalan Haywood\n| birth_name          = Kalan Haywood II\n| birth_date          = June 5, 1999 (age 20)\n| birth_place         = [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], U.S.\n| office              = Member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]]<br>from the 16th district\n| termstart           = January 2019\n| predecessor         = [[Leon Young]]\n| education           = [[Cardinal Stritch University]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n}}\n\n'''Kalan Haywood II''' is an American politician, currently serving as a member of the [[Wisconsin State Assembly]], representing the 16th Assembly District.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nHaywood was born on June 5, 1999 in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]. He graduated from the [[Rufus King International High School]] and is currently attending [[Cardinal Stritch University]] to earn a Bachelor of Arts degree in Business Administration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://docs.legis.wisconsin.gov/2019/legislators/assembly/1929|title=Representative Kalan Haywood|website=docs.legis.wisconsin.gov|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref> Haywood's father, Kalan Haywood Sr., is the founder of a real estate development firm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://onmilwaukee.com/raisemke/articles/nns-kalan-haywood.html|title=\"What are we waiting for?\" Service is a family affair for Haywoods|date=2019-07-28|work=OnMilwaukee.com|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nHaywood served as president of the City of Milwaukee Youth Council. He also worked as a non-profit consultant and was a member of the City of Milwaukee Restorative Justice Advisory Committee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Kalan_Haywood|title=Kalan Haywood|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\nHaywood was 19-years-old when he won the Democratic [[primary election]] in August 2018 and the unchallenged election in November 2018, making him the youngest person serving in the Wisconsin Assembly.<ref name=\"JSOnline\">[https://www.jsonline.com/story/news/politics/elections/2018/09/28/teen-youngest-lawmaker-wisconsin-and-nation/1280007002/ At 19, Kalan Haywood will be the youngest lawmaker in Wisconsin \u2014 and likely the nation], by Molly Beck, in the ''[[Milwaukee Journal-Sentinel]]''; published September 28, 2018; retrieved November 14, 2018</ref><ref name=\"WUWM\">[http://www.wuwm.com/post/wisconsin-partisan-primary-2018-election-results Wisconsin Partisan Primary 2018 Election Results], by Lauren Sigfusson; at [[WUWM]]; published August 14, 2018; retrieved November 14, 2018; \"No Republicans are running\"</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Taylor|first=Kate|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/13/us/young-candidates-elections.html|title=In New Class of Young Lawmakers, a Former Girl Scout Goes to the Statehouse|date=2018-11-13|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-17|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Wisconsin State Assembly}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haywood, Kalan}}\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Wisconsin State Assembly]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "KidAd", "label": "safe", "comment": "wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalan_Haywood"}
{"title_page": "COVID-19 Case-Cluster-Study", "text_new": "[[File:Hendrik Streeck.jpg|thumb|[[Hendrik Streeck]], principial investigator]]\nThe so-called '''COVID-19 Case-Cluster-Study''' \u2013 colloquially, '''Heinsberg study''', marketed as '''Heinsbergprotokoll''' and '''HEINSBERG&nbsp;PROTOKOLL.''' \u2013 is an unfinished and unpublished study about the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in [[Gangelt]].\n\nThe study was commissioned and is co-financed by the government of [[Northrhine-Westfalia]] and is led by [[Hendrik Streeck]]. In the [[public sphere]], the marketing agency [[StoryMachine]] advocates its results on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]]. Private enterprises also co-financed the study. First results of the study garnered cross-national media attention.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0261-3077| last1 = Sydney| first1 = Philip Oltermann Helen Davidson in| last2 = Orleans| first2 = Oliver Laughland in New| last3 = Bangkok| first3 = Rebecca Ratcliffe in| last4 = Paris| first4 = Joanna Walters in New York Kim Willsher in| last5 = Palermo| first5 = Lorenzo Tondo in| title = The cluster effect: how social gatherings were rocket fuel for coronavirus| work = The Guardian| accessdate = 2020-04-15| date = 2020-04-09| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/09/the-cluster-effect-how-social-gatherings-were-rocket-fuel-for-coronavirus}}<br />{{Cite web| last = Jones| first = Brandon G.| title = German study shows coronavirus mortality rate of 0.37%, five times lower than widely reported numbers| work = ABC 14 News| accessdate = 2020-04-15| date = 2020-04-09| url = https://abc14news.com/2020/04/09/german-study-shows-coronavirus-mortality-rate-of-0-37-five-times-lower-than-widely-reported-numbers/}}</ref>\n\nThe study aims to determine [[lethality]] of, and [[Immunity (medical)|immunity]] to [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]; it also estimates the number of unrecorded cases.<ref name=\"faz_1\">{{Cite news| issn = 0174-4909| last = Burger| first = Reiner| title = Ergebnisse ab n\u00e4chster Woche: Am Beispiel von Heinsberg die Pandemie verstehen| work = Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = 2020-03-27| url = https://www.faz.net/1.6699780}}</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that [[sample size]] does not determine the [[representativeness]] of a study,<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1111/cts.12178| issn = 1752-8054| volume = 7| issue = 4| pages = 342\u2013346| last1 = Kaplan| first1 = Robert M.| last2 = Chambers| first2 = David A.| last3 = Glasgow| first3 = Russell E.| title = Big Data and Large Sample Size: A Cautionary Note on the Potential for Bias| journal = Clinical and Translational Science| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = August 2014| url = http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/cts.12178}}</ref> principle investigator Streeck claims, they examined more persons than recommonended by the [[World Health Organization]], the study would \u201ethus be stastically absolutely representative.\u201c<ref>{{Cite web| last1 = Streeck| first1 = Hendrik| last2 = Jauch| first2 = Matthias| title = \"Die Ver\u00f6ffentlichung zu Heinsberg war nicht leichtfertig\"| format = Tagesspiegel| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = 2020-04-12| url = https://www.tagesspiegel.de/wissen/virologe-streeck-zur-coronavirus-studie-die-veroeffentlichung-zu-heinsberg-war-nicht-leichtfertig/25735672.html}} original text: \"also statistisch absolut repr\u00e4sentativ.\"</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany]]\n[[Category:German medical research]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n\n[[de:COVID-19 Case-Cluster-Study]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Hendrik Streeck.jpg|thumb|[[Hendrik Streeck]], principial investigator]]\nThe so-called '''COVID-19 Case-Cluster-Study''' \u2013 colloquially, '''Heinsberg study''', marketed as '''Heinsbergprotokoll''' and '''HEINSBERG&nbsp;PROTOKOLL.''' \u2013 is an unfinished and unpublished study about the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in [[Gangelt]].\n\nThe study was commissioned and is co-financed by the government of [[Northrhine-Westfalia]] and is led by [[Hendrik Streeck]]. In the [[public sphere]], the marketing agency [[StoryMachine]] advocates its results on [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]]. Private enterprises also co-financed the study. First results of the study garnered cross-national media attention.<ref>{{Cite news| issn = 0261-3077| last1 = Sydney| first1 = Philip Oltermann Helen Davidson in| last2 = Orleans| first2 = Oliver Laughland in New| last3 = Bangkok| first3 = Rebecca Ratcliffe in| last4 = Paris| first4 = Joanna Walters in New York Kim Willsher in| last5 = Palermo| first5 = Lorenzo Tondo in| title = The cluster effect: how social gatherings were rocket fuel for coronavirus| work = The Guardian| accessdate = 2020-04-15| date = 2020-04-09| url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/09/the-cluster-effect-how-social-gatherings-were-rocket-fuel-for-coronavirus}}<br />{{Cite web| last = Jones| first = Brandon G.| title = German study shows coronavirus mortality rate of 0.37%, five times lower than widely reported numbers| work = ABC 14 News| accessdate = 2020-04-15| date = 2020-04-09| url = https://abc14news.com/2020/04/09/german-study-shows-coronavirus-mortality-rate-of-0-37-five-times-lower-than-widely-reported-numbers/}}</ref>\n\nThe study aims to determine [[lethality]] of, and [[immunity]] to [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]; it also estimates the number of unrecorded cases.<ref name=\"faz_1\">{{Cite news| issn = 0174-4909| last = Burger| first = Reiner| title = Ergebnisse ab n\u00e4chster Woche: Am Beispiel von Heinsberg die Pandemie verstehen| work = Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = 2020-03-27| url = https://www.faz.net/1.6699780}}</ref>\n\nDespite the fact that [[sample size]] does not determine the [[representativeness]] of a study,<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1111/cts.12178| issn = 1752-8054| volume = 7| issue = 4| pages = 342\u2013346| last1 = Kaplan| first1 = Robert M.| last2 = Chambers| first2 = David A.| last3 = Glasgow| first3 = Russell E.| title = Big Data and Large Sample Size: A Cautionary Note on the Potential for Bias| journal = Clinical and Translational Science| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = August 2014| url = http://doi.wiley.com/10.1111/cts.12178}}</ref> principle investigator Streeck claims, they examined more persons than recommonended by the [[World Health Organization]], the study would \u201ethus be stastically absolutely representative.\u201c<ref>{{Cite web| last1 = Streeck| first1 = Hendrik| last2 = Jauch| first2 = Matthias| title = \"Die Ver\u00f6ffentlichung zu Heinsberg war nicht leichtfertig\"| format = Tagesspiegel| accessdate = 2020-04-16| date = 2020-04-12| url = https://www.tagesspiegel.de/wissen/virologe-streeck-zur-coronavirus-studie-die-veroeffentlichung-zu-heinsberg-war-nicht-leichtfertig/25735672.html}} original text: \"also statistisch absolut repr\u00e4sentativ.\"</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:COVID-19]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Germany]]\n[[Category:German medical research]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n\n[[de:COVID-19 Case-Cluster-Study]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_Case-Cluster-Study"}
{"title_page": "1978 in literature", "text_new": "{{Year nav topic5|1978|literature|poetry}}\n\nThis article presents lists of the literary events and publications in '''1978'''.\n<!-- Redlinks will be removed. They make no sense in a list. Add pages as you write them. -->\n==Events==\n*[[March 8]] \u2013 [[Douglas Adams]]' [[comic science fiction]] series ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]'' originates as a [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy (radio series)|radio comedy]] broadcast on [[BBC Radio 4]] in the U.K.\n*March \u2013 [[Philip Larkin]] ends his relationships with Maeve Brennan and Betty Mackereth.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Bradford |first=Richard |title=First Boredom Then Fear: The Life of Philip Larkin |publication-place=London |publisher=Peter Owen |isbn=0-7206-1147-4 |year=2004 |page=245}}</ref>\n*April \u2013 [[James Blaylock]]'s first published story, \"The Ape-Box Affair\" in ''Unearth'' magazine, pioneers [[steampunk]] fiction.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.sf-encyclopedia.com/entry/blaylock_james_p |title=Blaylock, James P |website=Encyclopedia of Science Fiction |date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=27 May 2016}}</ref>\n*[[August 1]] \u2013 [[Barbara Pym]] is a guest on ''[[Desert Island Discs]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |author1=Jerry Dowlen |title=The very best Christmas features... Jerry Dowlen celebrates the life and centenary of Barbara Pym... |url=http://www.booksmonthly.co.uk/jd.html |website=booksmonthly.co.uk |publisher=Paul Norman |accessdate=April 5, 2015 |format=monthly literary column |date=December 2013 |quote=Barbara Pym's appearance on ''Desert Island Discs'' on 1 August 1978 was replayed on BBC Radio 4 Extra on 2 June 2013}}</ref>\n*October \u2013 The [[Bookseller/Diagram Prize for Oddest Title of the Year]], a humorous award given annually to books with unusual titles, is launched at the [[Frankfurt Book Fair]]. The first winner is ''Proceedings of the Second International Workshop on Nude Mice''.<ref>{{Cite magazine |last=Bent |first=Horace |url=http://www.thebookseller.com/in-depth/feature/107456-a-bluffers-guide-to-the-diagram-prize.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201222523/http://thebookseller.com/in-depth/feature/107456-a-bluffers-guide-to-the-diagram-prize.html |archivedate=1 December 2010 |title=A Bluffer's Guide to the Diagram Prize |magazine=The Bookseller |date=21 October 2009 |accessdate=21 December 2009}}</ref>\n*[[November 15]] \u2013 [[Harold Pinter]]'s play ''[[Betrayal (play)|Betrayal]]'', inspired by his seven-year clandestine extramarital affair with [[BBC Television]] presenter [[Joan Bakewell]], opens at the [[Royal National Theatre|National Theatre]] in London, directed by [[Peter Hall (director)|Peter Hall]] and featuring [[Penelope Wilton]] and her husband at this time, [[Daniel Massey (actor)|Daniel Massey]], with [[Michael Gambon]].<ref>{{Cite book |authorlink=Michael Billington (critic) |last=Billington |first=Michael |title=Harold Pinter |edition=Rev. |year=2007 |location=London |publisher=Faber and Faber |isbn=9780571234769}}</ref>\n\n''Uncertain date''\n*The [[Berlin State Library]]'s new ''Haus Potsdamer Stra\u00dfe'' is completed and opened in [[West Berlin]]'s [[Kulturforum]].\n\n==New books==\n===Fiction===\n*[[Etel Adnan]] \u2013 ''[[Sitt Marie Rose]]''\n*[[Srikrishna Alanahalli]] \u2013 ''Parasangada Gendethimma''\n*[[Kingsley Amis]] \u2013 ''[[Jake's Thing]]''\n*[[Martin Amis]] \u2013 ''[[Success (novel)|Success]]''\n*[[Jessica Anderson]] \u2013 ''[[Tirra Lirra by the River]]''\n*[[Aharon Appelfeld]] \u2013 ''[[Badenheim 1939]]'' (\u05d1\u05d0\u05d3\u05e0\u05d4\u05d9\u05d9\u05dd&nbsp;\u05e2\u05d9\u05e8&nbsp;\u05e0\u05d5\u05e4\u05e9, ''Badenhaim `ir nofesh'')\n*[[Richard Bach]] \u2013 ''[[Illusions (Bach novel)|Illusions]]''\n*[[Beryl Bainbridge]] \u2013 ''[[Young Adolf]]''\n*[[Thomas Berger (novelist)|Thomas Berger]] \u2013 ''[[Arthur Rex: A Legendary Novel]]''\n*[[Thomas Bernhard]] \u2013 ''[[Yes (novel)|Yes]]'' (''Ja'')\n*[[Adolfo Bioy Casa